observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the:

Municipal Mayor should issue an order for the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of all properties of the Municipality and submit the RCPPE as of December 31, 2020 on or before September 30, 2021, in accordance with Section 6.1 and 6.2 of COA Circular No. 2020-006; 

We also recommended that the GSO, in coordination with the Accounting Department, should: 

Reconcile its property records with that of the RPCPPE in accordance with the provisions of Section 6.3 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 and after completing the reconciliation procedures, the total reconciled balances for each PPE account shall be established as the correct balance of PPE at year-end; and 

Undergo disposal procedures for non-existing/missing PPEs, if there are any, in accordance with Section 7 of COA Circular No. 2020-006; 

Lastly, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant should: 

Re-compute the depreciation of all depreciable assets and draw an adjusting entry to set the accounts in order. Henceforth, provide for the correct depreciation expense for the subject properties.

Together with the GSO, prepare, maintain and update all necessary monitoring records and reports for PPEs as required in the IPSAS, COA Circular No. 2020-006 and other standards. 

Record accounting entries for the recognition of PPEs found at station, recognition of loss of PPEs, writing-off/dropping from the books of accounts the remaining balances amounts lumped under the reconciled SLs of PPEs, and derecognition of non-existing/missing items;

Present the necessary disclosures on PPE in the Notes to the Financial Statements; 





Transfer PPEs in the Trust Fund to General Fund and provide depreciation thereto.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant should: 

Record all supplies procured in the appropriate Inventory account upon purchase; 

Record the consumed or distributed supplies expenses upon receipt of the RSMI from the GSO supported with the RIS; and 


Reconcile monthly with the records from the GSO to confirm the balances of Inventories in its books with the balance on hand. 

We also recommended that the General Services Officer should:  
Prepare Stock Card upon acceptance of the supplies; 


Issue RIS upon release of the supplies to the end-users; 


Submit monthly to the Municipal Accountant the Consolidated RSMI duly supported with the RIS; and 


Reconcile monthly with the Municipal Accountant to confirm balances on hand.

We recommended that the MDRRMO prepare the LDRRMFIP annually to support the budget for LDRRMF and the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF to account for the funds and submit the same to the Audit Team on or before the 15th of the month. 

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Record in the Trust Fund books using the Trust Liabilities-DRRMF account, the transfers of unexpended QRF and the DRRM-MOOE funds; 


Revert back to the General Fund the unutilized LDRRMF after five (5) years which will be made available for funding other social services expenditure;

Prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers; 

We also recommended that the Municipal Budget Officer prepare and maintain separate registry for LDRRMF-QRF, MOOE and CO.

We recommended the following corrective measures: 

The Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accountant with the complete description and cost segregation of road components to facilitate the preparation of the subsidiary ledgers for such account; 

The Municipal Accountant reclassify the affected accounts, prepare the necessary ledgers, the schedules and reports as called for in the afore-cited Circular; 

The Inventory Committee conduct a physical count on all municipal roads of the Municipality to validate their existence; and 

All offices concerned to reconcile their records in order to come-up with an accurate and reliable balances and reports.

We recommend that the Municipal Accountant perform the following actions: 

Determine the conditions of the dormant accounts and validate the existence and conditions by obtaining the applicable documents as enumerated in Section 8.3b of COA Circular No. 2016-005; 

Prepare the Schedule of Dormant Accounts by Accountable Officer/debtor/government entity and by account, certify its correctness and have it approved by the Head of the government entity; 

Prepare the request for write-off of the receivable accounts and submit to the Municipal Mayor, with supporting document, for approval and submission to COA.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
require the Inventory Committee and instruct its members to conduct a complete physical count of all properties of the LGU for one-time cleansing of the PPE accounts marking each PPE item as government property;
prepare and submit the RPCPPE to the Municipal Accountant copy furnish the Audit Team on or before October 31, 2022, to afford reconciliation with the records in the Accounting Office to arrive at an accurate balance of the PPE accounts in the financial statements;
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant and MGS Officer maintain an updated and reconciled PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, to support the amount for each item comprising the PPE account.  Differences noted shall be verified and the corrections be made, where necessary.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Submit to the Audit Team an explanation for the non-implementation of the programmed PPAs as embodied in the Annual Investment/ Development Plan;
implement immediately all the projects under the continuing appropriation;
as Chairperson of the Local Development Council, ensure that all savings from completed PPAs and appropriations of all PPAs which are no longer feasible for implementation be considered for realignment, subject to budgetary rules and regulations or reverted back to unappropriated surplus of the 20% DF for re-appropriation to other development projects; and
include only 20% DF PPAs which are feasible and could be accomplished within the target date of completion after taking into consideration the priorities of the Municipality.
We also recommended that the MPD Coordinator shall closely monitor and evaluate the implementation of the various development PPAs identified in the approved Local Development Plan as required in Section 476 (4) of R.A. 7160.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Require the Municipal Engineer to submit explanation, for the Audit Team’s evaluation, on the non-conduct of preliminary engineering survey before the preparation of the Program of Work for these road projects constructed at Barangays Cabaliwan, Libas, Libjo and Benabaye;
Henceforth, require the Municipal Engineer to conduct preliminary engineering study before the preparation of the Program of Work for every infrastructure project of the LGU;
Also, require the contractors to submit “as built plans” on the projects discussed in paragraph numbers 9.3 and 9.4;
We also recommended that the Inspectorate Team should exercise due diligence in the inspection of completed projects to make sure that the projects were completed in accordance with the specifications in the approved POWs.
We further recommended that the Municipal Accountant require the Contractors to submit an “As Built” plans as attachment to the final payment of contractor’s claims.

We recommended that the Chairperson of the BAC submit to the Audit Team an explanation on the deficiencies discussed in paragraph numbers 14.6, 14.7, 14.9 to 14.12,   and henceforth:
Transact only with suppliers which are PhilGEPS registered;
Resolution awarding the Winning Bidder shall be prepared separately;
Post the Notice of Awards, Contract or POs for transactions amounting to ₱50,000.00 and above at the PhilGEPS website, LGUs website if any, and at any conspicuous places in the premises of the LGU;
Reproduce the postings made and attach the same in the DVs to be submitted to Accounting and COA office; and
Fill out all the required forms for procurement.
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Submit written explanation why these transactions were recommended for approval by the Municipal Mayor despite the deficiencies noted above; and
Henceforth, ensure that all procurement documents are completely and properly filled out before forwarding the DV to the Municipal Mayor for approval.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant should:

Prepare the Disbursement Voucher immediately to transfer the unexpended balance of P920,346.69 to the appropriate account under the Trust Fund in accordance with the provisions of the IRR of RA No. 10121 and COA Circular No. 2012-002 to safeguard the resources against risk misuse/misappropriations; 

Revert back to the General Fund the unutilized LDRRMF after five (5) year amounting to ₱446,981.43 to which will be made available to fund other social services; 
Reclassify the account used to record the previous years’ transfer from Due to Other Funds to trust Liabilities-DRRMF; and

Regularly reconcile the record on LDRRM Fund balance with the records from the Municipal Budget Office.

We recommended that the Municipal Treasurer. In coordination with the Municipal Accountant, strengthen the internal control in handling the cash, following the procedures provided in Section 63 of Local Treasury Operation Manual and COA Circular No. 92-382, viz:

Collections should be performed by duly authorized Collectors and they should prepare the Report of Collections and Deposit to be submitted daily to the Liquidating Officer together with the daily collections; 

Collectors should maintain their own Cashbooks, to record collections received (debit column) and all remittances to the designated Liquidating Officer (credit column); 

Liquidating Officer should check the statement of accountable forms as to initial balances on hand; make a physical count of the accountable forms remaining in the custody of the collector/teller and check the same to the new balances on hand column. She shall indicate her verification copy of the last official receipt issued. She shall count the money turned over to her and sign the certification and receipt portion of all copies of the DSCAF;

Liquidating Officer should maintain a Cashbook to record all collections turned over to her by the Collectors, Field and Market Collector 9debit column) and remittances to the Local Treasurer (credit column); 

Municipal Treasurer should deposit intact with the authorized depositary bank daily or not later than the next banking day, all her collections, as well as collections turned over to her by the Liquidating Officer. 

We further recommended that the Local Chief Executive or his duly authorized officials investigate or inquiry on the matter and review the ethical and professional conduct of employees concerned and if warranted, relieve the erring employee from her present duties and responsibilities, without prejudice to the filing of an administrative or criminal action.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, as Chairman of the Local Development Council, and the Municipal Planning and Development Officer: 

Review and evaluate all projects funded from the Continuing Appropriations of the 20% Development Fund; 

Re-appropriate the funds for other necessary projects if the PPAs lined up in previous years are no longer feasible.

We recommended that the designated Custodians of each requisitioning office: 

Prepare the RIS when supplies are issued to end-user/patients; 

Prepare and submit to the GSO the SSMI every 5th day of the month, duly supported with the corresponding RIS in numerical sequence; 

Maintain an updated stock card;

We recommend that the Municipal Accountant perform the following actions:

Determine the conditions of the dormant accounts and validate the existence of the conditions by obtaining the applicable documents as enumerated in Section 8.3b of COA Circular No. 2016-005;

     Prepare the Schedule of Dormant Accounts by Accountable Officer /debtor/government entity and by account, certify its correctness and have it approved by the Head of the government entity;

     Prepare the request for write-off of the receivable accounts and submit to the Municipal Mayor, with the necessary supporting document, for approval and submission to COA.

We recommend that the Municipal Mayor require the focal persons of the programs/projects to:

      coordinate with each source agency and obtain copies of the Memorandum of Agreement and Work and Financial Plan and furnish the same to the Municipal Accountant and the Audit Team;   

    fast track the completion of the programs and projects assigned to them so that full liquidation can be submitted; 

coordinate with the Municipal Accountant so that the corresponding liquidation reports will be prepared and submitted to the source agencies.

We also recommend that the Municipal Treasurer determine the availability of cash of all funds received from NGAs, especially the balances of completed programs/projects and those which has not been fully liquidated in the books of the LGU and issue the check in favor of the source agencies to return all remaining balances and unutilized amount.

In order to prevent the conclusion of irregular as well as invalid performance of duties concerning submission of accounts and avoid penalties provided for the contradictions of relevant laws and rules, the implementation of hereunder recommendations is proposed, viz:

Instruct the accountant to immediately submit all accounts to the Audit Team as specified by laws and regulations;

Instruct the treasurer and all accountable officers to practice the submission of accounts to the Accounting Office within the reglementary period, the same to be covered with transmittal letters as proof thereof.

We recommend that the Municipal Accountant to:

coordinate with each depository bank of the LGU for the early receipt of monthly bank statements or snapshot to facilitate the timely preparation of bank reconciliation statements;

prepare the necessary adjusting entries on all valid reconciling items in the BRS;

reconcile accounting records with Treasurer’s cashbook at least every quarter and make the necessary corrections on errors detected;

close dormant accounts under the Trust Fund and return to the source agencies any excess amount.  If no longer traceable, transfer such funds to regular operating funds as additional income.  

   We recommend that the Municipal Treasurer prepare a separate cashbook for LDRRMF and DAR-ARCP II (LGU Equity) accounts.

We recommend that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Assessor to:

perform his duties strictly by continuously updating the Assessment Rolls as to the conditions of the real properties, identify the exact addresses of declared owners of such properties, the exemptions on RPT, if any;


furnish the Municipal Treasurer with  the Assessment Rolls within the prescribed period;

continuously make a proper representation with concerned provincial officials with regards to the general revision of market value of the real properties in the municipality;
